ls in response to the threat posed by heretical Christians, in particular the Cathars. The white monks, withother intellectuals, turned to pen, pulpit and popular preaching to counteract heresy, some accepting posts as bishops and papal legates, helping and even directing the Albigensian crusade, and contributing to the formulation ofprocedures for inquisition. Kienzle examines this important but little-studied aspect of Cistercian history to discover how and why the Order undertook endeavours that drew the monks outside their monastic vocation. The analysis of texts about the preaching campaigns and their contexts illuminate the ways in which medieval monastic authors perceived heresy, preached, and wrote against it.Professor BEVERLY MAYNE KIENZLE teaches at Harvard Divinity School.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAlbigenses. 0aChristian heresiesxFrance, SouthernxHistory, Middle Ages, 600-1500. 0aChristian heresieszFrance, SouthernxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aSermons, MedievalxFrance, SouthernxHistory and criticism. 0aSermons, MedievalzFrance, SouthernxHistory and criticism. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAlbigensian Crusade.  aBernard of Clairvaux.  aCathars.  aCistercian Order.  aCistercian history.  aheresy.  aheretical Christians.  ainquisition.  apapal legates.  asouthern France.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615337240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846153372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846153372/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles